I've just pushed an update to this followup that tweaks and adds a couple methods so that you can form a few common interfaces between the dcmtime types. For instance, you can now write a helper function like this:

```go
// DCMTime is a common interface for dcmtime.Date, dcmtime.Time, and dcmtime.Datetime.
type DCMTime interface {
	GetTime() time.Time
	GetPrecision() dcmtime.PrecisionLevel
	DCM() string
}

func InspectDICOMTimeVal(value DCMTime) error {
	// Do something with this value
	return nil
}
```

The main addition here is adding a `GetTime()` and `GetPrecision()` method to each of the dcmtime types. I've been writing some code where a single code path could be used with an interface like this, so I decided it was worth adding in. Callers could do this though wrappers on their own, but having it right out of the box is kind of nice, IMO.

I realize that I am kind of bloating this PR, so let me know if you would like me to try and break this up into smaller PRs.
Thanks!

another pattern to consider. What if we kept a channel approach but wrapped it in a struct that satisfied `io.Closer`? So, we wouldn't have to implement a stateful iterator but 

```go
// Usage looks like
iter := dicom.FlatIterator()
defer iter.Close()
for element := range iter.chan {
    // ...
}
```

I suppose this is approximately similar to the creating a context and remembering to cancel it, though maybe a bit more explicit (and is similar to other patterns that use `io.Closer`). I'll check into this, but many linters and vet tools may even warn that Close() wasn't called if a user forgets it (not true in the context case if a user just passes context.Background() blindly). This is also a little more compact. I'll think on this a little and make some prototypes but let me know if you have a preference. I'm not sure I love this API either

Theres also another option:

Rather than implementing this as an iterator, we could just return a flattened slice of elements, so the signature is something
more akin to:

```go
func (d *Dataset) Flattened() []*Element {
    // implementation
}
```
Where all the elements are pre-collected for you. Because no io is involved, it's not clear to me that using a more complicated iterator approach will be so much more performant that it will really make a difference, especially weighed against the extra complexity. Maybe we start here, and add an iterator version at a later date?

It might be worth benching a simple approach like this against an iterator, which has its own overhead, to see if there are any worthwhile gains of using an iterator in the first place. I imagine most callers are going to want to inspect all elements on the happy path, so an iterator may only give a significant boost on error-paths, which will be less common, and therefore less important to optimize, anyway.

Okay, here is a second pass. I'll copy and paste the godoc exampled here to illustrate the API.

## Changes Overview

- Removed Raw fields. DICOM value strings are now generated on command
- New... constructor methods removed.
- WithNullSeparators() and WithoutNullSeparators() methods added for easy coercion to adding or removing all null separators when creating the Dicom value with .String()

## Examples

### Parse DICOM Value

```
// How to parse an existing PN value.
func ExampleParse() {
	// A Raw PN string value with Alphabetic, Ideographic, and Phonetic information.
	rawPN := "Potter^Harry^James^^=哈利^波特^詹姆^^=hɛər.i^pɒ.tər^dʒeɪmz^^"

	// To parse a PN value, use personName.Parse
	parsedPN, err := personname.Parse(rawPN)
	if err != nil {
		panic(err)
	}

	// PN values are broken into three groups: Alphabetic, Phonetic, and Ideographic.
	// which can be accessed through getter methods.
	fmt.Println("ALPHABETIC:", parsedPN.Alphabetic.String())
	fmt.Println("IDEOGRAPHIC:", parsedPN.Ideographic.String())
	fmt.Println("PHONETIC:", parsedPN.Phonetic.String())

	// Each Group info in turn has Getter methods for retrieving individual data.
	fmt.Println("FAMILY NAME:", parsedPN.Alphabetic.FamilyName)
	fmt.Println("GIVEN NAME: ", parsedPN.Alphabetic.GivenName)
	fmt.Println("MIDDLE NAME:", parsedPN.Alphabetic.MiddleName)
	fmt.Println("NAME PREFIX:", parsedPN.Alphabetic.NamePrefix)
	fmt.Println("NAME SUFFIX:", parsedPN.Alphabetic.NameSuffix)

	// To print the original Raw value, simply use the string method.
	fmt.Println("ORIGINAL RAW:", parsedPN.String())

	// Output (gotest comparison here is busted, maybe due to ideographs?):
	// ALPHABETIC: Potter^Harry^James^^
	// IDEOGRAPHIC: 哈利^波特^詹姆^^
	// PHONETIC: hɛər.i^pɒ.tər^dʒeɪmz^^
	// FAMILY NAME: Potter
	// GIVEN NAME:  Harry
	// MIDDLE NAME: James
	// NAME PREFIX:
	// NAME SUFFIX:
	// ORIGINAL RAW: Potter^Harry^James^^=哈利^波特^詹姆^^=hɛər.i^pɒ.tər^dʒeɪmz^^
}
```

### Create New PN

```
// How to create new PN value.
func ExampleNew() {
	// Create a new PN like so
	pnVal := personname.Info{
		Alphabetic: personname.GroupInfo{
			FamilyName: "Potter",
			GivenName:  "Harry",
			MiddleName: "James",
		},
		// Add empty group that will not render its separators.
		Ideographic: personname.GroupInfo{
			NoNullSeparators: true,
		},
		// Add empty group that will not render its separators.
		Phonetic: personname.GroupInfo{
			NoNullSeparators: true,
		},
		// This will remove trailing '=' separators
		NoNullSeparators: true,
	}

	// Print the string, should render as 'Potter^Harry^James^^'.
	fmt.Println("PN 1:", pnVal.String())

	// Now let's make one that still renders empty groups with String().
	pnVal = personname.Info{
		Alphabetic: personname.GroupInfo{
			FamilyName: "Potter",
			GivenName:  "Harry",
			MiddleName: "James",
		},
		// Add empty group that will render its separators.
		Ideographic: personname.GroupInfo{},
		// Add empty group that will render its separators.
		Phonetic: personname.GroupInfo{},
	}

	// This will render as 'Potter^Harry^James^^=^^^^=^^^^'
	fmt.Println("PN 2:", pnVal.String())

	// Output:
	// PN 1: Potter^Harry^James^^
	// PN 2: Potter^Harry^James^^=^^^^=^^^^
}
```

### Reformat

```
func ExampleInfo_WithNullSeparators() {
	rawVal := "Potter^Harry"

	parsedPN, err := personname.Parse(rawVal)
	if err != nil {
		panic(err)
	}

	fmt.Println("ORIGINAL   :", parsedPN.String())

	reformatted := parsedPN.WithNullSeparators()
	fmt.Println("REFORMATTED:", reformatted.String())

	// Output:
	// ORIGINAL   : Potter^Harry
	// REFORMATTED: Potter^Harry^^^=^^^^=^^^^
}
```

```
func ExampleInfo_WithoutNullSeparators() {
	rawVal := "Potter^Harry^^^=^^^^=^^^^"

	parsedPN, err := personname.Parse(rawVal)
	if err != nil {
		panic(err)
	}

	fmt.Println("ORIGINAL   :", parsedPN.String())

	reformatted := parsedPN.WithoutNullSeparators()
	fmt.Println("REFORMATTED:", reformatted.String())

	// Output:
	// ORIGINAL   : Potter^Harry^^^=^^^^=^^^^
	// REFORMATTED: Potter^Harry
}
```

## Open Questions

### Do we want .String() to return something more human-friendly?

I started out thinking this was a no-brainer good idea: the current .String() method could be turned into a DCM() method, and the string could return something easier to interpret at-a-glance.

The more I think about it, though, the less certain I become.

My first instinct would be:

'[NamePrefix] [FirstName] [MiddleName] [GivenName] [NameSuffix]'

But is that an Anglo-centric solution. I believe other cultures prefer to lead with the Family name, and am less certain on traditions surrounding titles (in Japanese, titles come after the name for instance). Further complicating things, I am unsure how other cultural conventions would map to the DICOM spec. Do Japanese hospitals use Mr. and Mrs.? Or do they use -San? Do they put that in the NamePrefix or NameSuffix field? The spec also specifically defined 'Given Name' instead of 'Last Name', which implies sensitivity that these fields need to support non-anglo names. Where should the Given Name be put, then?

Would using the above format result in something that borders nonsensical in certain non-English settings?

Humans are opinionated, and it's quite likely that there would be many, many divergent opinions on the best way to pretty-string this value, even in an English setting.

So where did I end up?

It is valid to say that these helper modules are here to implement the parsing of a value in accordance with the DICOM spec, and pretty-printing that value -- while tempting to include -- is outside that scope.

We may even want to define a DCM() and remove String() to side-step the whole problem and make clear we are not solving for it. Non-DICOM-compliant string representations can be left completely to the end user and their preferences.

> Can you help shed a little more light on this use case? Typically, why would a caller want to know if null separators were used? Would it sufficient to have a helper function just for that?

I'm not sure I had a hard reason for this beyond a philosophical one: I think, where possible, it's good to preserve all of the data inherent in an encoding, so that there is no information lost -- meaning you can fully recreate / re-encode your parsed data into the same serialized representation, as anything other behavior could be surprising to the caller, and as such result in a latent bug that goes undetected until you hit an edge case that might have downstream effects.

> Can you shed more light on why most callers would want this behavior? Is there some worry that writing the value back out without trailing null separators may cause a problem in the source system, even though it's conformant with the DICOM standard? 

One of the things I really like about pydicom is that when you get a value like a PersonName object, if you stick it back into another DICOM the original value will not be altered, even if it is non-compliant. They do that by carrying around the original string value in their value classes.

There are a LOT of legacy systems out there, some self-coded tools, etc, where certain assumptions may have been made about the way a value is formatted for that shop, where altering the way a value is represented in some other system might cause issues. In other words, system where the internal expectation is more strict than what the DICOM spec allows for. I've seen this be the case with all sorts of interchange formats in industry: proprietary tools make certain assumptions specific to an org, and if you don't preserve data exactly as-is when possible, your may cause issues for overly-fitted systems.

In an ideal world, that would not be an issue, but in the real world it often is. People abuse metadata fields all the time to 'encode' additional information.

Here's a couple theoretical examples I can think of off the top of my head:

**Querying a System**

Lets say we have a dicom with a weirdly formatted patient name we store in a db somewhere:

```
	// Let's say we have an element with an odd PN value
	element, err := dicom.NewElement(tag.PersonName, []string{"Potter^Harry^"})
	if err != nil {
		panic(err)
	}

	// We then parse that value as a personname.Info
	pnRaw := element.Value.GetValue().([]string)[0]
	pnVal, err := personname.Parse(pnRaw)
	if err != nil {
		panic(pnRaw)
	}

	// Then we store it in a database somewhere
	recordId, err := storeInDB(pnVal)
	if err != nil {
		panic(err)
	}
```

In our storage stage, we store the PN val in its component parts as parsed in personname.Info. Later on, we fetch that record, and reconstitute the value, then make a query to the PACS system for other images for patients of the same name (normally you would do this by patent ID, but you might know this patient has two different ID's or the like):

```
	recordId, err := storeInDB(pnVal)
	if err != nil {
		panic(err)
	}

	pnVal, err := getFromDB(recordId)
	if err != nil {
		panic(err)
	}
	
	resultList, err := queryPACSForName(tag.PatientName, pnVal.DCM())
	if err != nil {
		panic(err)
	}
```

If we don't fully capture the information contained in the PN value here, then it may lead to us querying for information with a value different from the original.

Or, what if we are batch-modifying a bunch of scans, while also logging our progress? We might read in a patient name formatted oddly, then write it to the new file, where we have been trying just to zap other fields by building a new Dataset without them, and after the fact notice that the formatting on all of our names has changed, causing problems somewhere else.

That being said, I DO agree that it might be simpler is better. Storing the discreet level of null separators is a little bit more overhead for creating new PN values, and because of the way enums are handled in go, pollutes the namespace a bit.

But, by fully capturing the data, it allows users to be able to use the structure as a round-trip data parser without having to worry about the serialized format being altered, something I generally think of as a bug from a decode / encode perspective, and that might be surprising behavior to the caller, which it is also important to avoid.

And again I keep falling back to: I would like to FULLY capture the encoding laid out in the dicom spec, and for better or worse the DICOM spec specifically allows for this truncation feature, so a FULL implementation of a PN constructor should have a way to set your preference.

