Hi @BennicTV,

So the [getChampionById](https://developer.riotgames.com/api-methods/#lol-static-data-v3/GET_getChampionById) Riot Games API endpoint that backs the method you are calling doesn't return all data by default. The default response will only contain the champions name, title, id, and key.

You are currently using the method that asks for the default response:

```java
getDataChampion(Platform platform, int id);
```

To ask for more information than this, you will have to use the overloaded method, and provide additional 'tags' for the kind of data you wish to receive.

```java
 getDataChampion(Platform platform, int id, Locale locale, String version, ChampionTags... tags);
```

So your updated code might look something like this:

```java
Champion champion = api.getDataChampion(Platform.EUW, ID, null, null,
                ChampionTags.STATS, ChampionTags.PASSIVE, ChampionTags.LORE, ChampionTags.SKINS);
```

Alternatively, if you don't care too much about controlling the payload size of the response from the API, you can just provide `ChampionTags.ALL` as a tag to get all the possible champion data.

```java
Champion champion = api.getDataChampion(Platform.EUW, ID, null, null, ChampionTags.ALL);
```

To answer your second question, it is totally possible to create a program that looks up champion information by champion name.

You will still be querying for champion data using the champion's ID (as that is the unique identifier for the champion that the endpoint for the Riot Games API expects you to provide), however the trick it to make a request for all champion data and cache this data before the user asks you for a specific champion's data.

The Riot Games API provides a great endpoint to retrieve data for all champions in the game. The method for this endpoint is called `getDataChampionList`:

```java
ChampionList championList = api.getDataChampionList(Platform.EUW, null, null, false, ChampionListTags.ALL);
```

Unfortunately, the data is organized as a mapping from champion `key` to champion data objects, and keys aren't always the champion's name (i.e. Wukong's key is MonkeyKing). So, if you want to cache this data in a way that makes it easy to retrieve champion data by their name in a scalable way, you will have to get a bit fancy and use your own data structure as a cache rather than just using the map directly from the response.

Here's a simple example:

```java
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.Scanner;
import net.rithms.riot.api.ApiConfig;
import net.rithms.riot.api.RiotApi;
import net.rithms.riot.api.RiotApiException;
import net.rithms.riot.api.endpoints.static_data.constant.ChampionListTags;
import net.rithms.riot.api.endpoints.static_data.dto.Champion;
import net.rithms.riot.api.endpoints.static_data.dto.ChampionList;
import net.rithms.riot.constant.Platform;

public class GetDataChampionExample {

    private static Scanner scanner;

    public static void main(String[] args) throws RiotApiException {
        ApiConfig config = new ApiConfig().setKey("key");
        RiotApi api = new RiotApi(config);

        ChampionList championList = api.getDataChampionList(Platform.EUW, null, null, false, ChampionListTags.ALL);
        Map<String, Champion> championByName = new HashMap<>();
        for (Champion champion : championList.getData().values()) {
            championByName.put(champion.getName().toLowerCase(), champion);
        }

        scanner = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.print("What champion would you like data for?");
        String name = scanner.next().toLowerCase();
        Champion champion = championByName.get(name);
        if (champion != null) {
            System.out.println("ID: " + champion.getId());
            System.out.println("Name: " + champion.getName());
            System.out.println("Stats: " + champion.getStats());
            System.out.println("Passive: " + champion.getPassive());
            System.out.println("Lore: " + champion.getLore());
            System.out.println("Title: " + champion.getTitle());
            System.out.println("Skins: " + champion.getSkins());
        } else {
            System.out.println("Sorry I don't recognize that champion name.");
        }
    }
}
```

